<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-201-051 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 608 963</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Design  March 14 1991 v39 n5 p45(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>High-density programmable logic takes on gate arrays. (includesrelated articles on software tools and complex-architecturevariations)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bursky, Dave.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Large field-programmable chips give designers the ability tocreate a functional prototype almost instantly.andP;  A largefield-programmable gate array (FPGA) has a higher per-unit costthan a mass-produced gate array, but the non-recurring-engineeringcosts are much lower so the FPGA is suitable for small to moderateproduction runs.andP;  Challenges facing FPGAs include reducing on-shipsignal-propagation delays, improving circuit implementationflexibility, and increasing the gate count.andP;  As densitiesincrease, the trend is an almost complete shift away from bipolartechnology.andP;  Designers are relying more and more on good softwaretools that hide architectures from systems designers and permitthem to work at the macrocell level.andP;  UV EPROM-based programmablelogic chips are competing with the RAM and anti-fuse arrays.andO;Field-programmable chips are starting to replace masked gatearrays.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Gate ArraysTrendsIntegrated CircuitsDesign.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Enhanced configurable logic block. (chart)Logic-array blocks. (chart)Manufacturers of high-density field-programmable logic. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>